Tidyverse overview

Magrittr

The R pipe operator, also known as the magrittr pipe operator, is a powerful tool in the R programming language that enhances the readability and efficiency of code by allowing the output of one function to serve as the input for another function. Denoted by the %>% symbol, the pipe operator enables a more fluent and sequential coding style, where data flows through a series of transformations or operations. With the pipe operator, you can avoid intermediate variables and nested function calls, making code more concise and easier to understand. By chaining functions together using the pipe operator, you can create a clear and intuitive data processing pipeline, improving the overall readability and maintainability of your R code.

Pipe operator %>%

Function chaining, or composition, is a powerful concept that allows you to combine two functions, such as \(f: B \to C\) and \(g: A \to B\), by feeding the output of one function as the input to the next. In simple terms, chaining involves passing an intermediate result from one function to the subsequent function in the sequence. For instance, consider the expression \(f(g(x))\), where \(x\) is the input for \(g()\), and \(g(x)\) serves as the input for \(f()\). This notation signifies that the output of \(g()\) is being processed by \(f()\). To represent this concept, the notation \(f \circ g\) is used, which can be read as “f follows g.” It signifies the sequential order of applying functions.

the common syntax for functions are:

\(functionname(dataframeinput, arguments) \to dataframeoutput\)

now using the pipe operator:

\(dataframeinput\) %>% \(functionname(arguments) \to dataframeoutput\)

as we can see offers a set of operators which make your code more readable by:

  • structuring sequences of data operations left-to-right (as opposed to from the inside and out)
  • avoiding nested function calls
  • minimizing the need for local variables and function definitions
  • making it easy to add steps anywhere in the sequence of operations.

Tidyr

The goal of tidyr is to help you create tidy data. Tidy data is data where:

Every column is variable. Every row is an observation. Every cell is a single value.

Tidy data describes a standard way of storing data that is used wherever possible throughout the tidyverse. If you ensure that your data is tidy, you’ll spend less time fighting with the tools and more time working on your analysis. Learn more about tidy data in vignette(“tidy-data”).

Dplyr

dplyr is a grammar of data manipulation, providing a consistent set of verbs that help you solve the most common data manipulation challenges:

  • mutate() adds new variables that are functions of existing variables
  • select() picks variables based on their names.
  • filter() picks cases based on their values.
  • summarise() reduces multiple values down to a single summary.
  • arrange() changes the ordering of the rows.

These all combine naturally with group_by() which allows you to perform any operation “by group”. You can learn more about them in vignette(“dplyr”). As well as these single-table verbs, dplyr also provides a variety of two-table verbs, which you can learn about in vignette(“two-table”).

Lubridate

Date-time data can be frustrating to work with in R. R commands for date-times are generally unintuitive and change depending on the type of date-time object being used. Moreover, the methods we use with date-times must be robust to time zones, leap days, daylight savings times, and other time related quirks, and R lacks these capabilities in some situations. Lubridate makes it easier to do the things R does with date-times and possible to do the things R does not.
